definition.value: Any N-acetylhexosamine in which the hexosamine has D-configuration. The structure provided is an illustrative example of the pyranose form of an N-acetyl-D-hexosamine.
Any N-acylamino acid having L-configuration.
Any optically active N-acylglutamic acid having L-configuration.
A N-acyl-hexosamine in which the acyl group specified is glycoloyl.
A glycosyl compound arising formally from the elimination of water from a glycosidic hydroxy group and an H atom bound to a nitrogen atom, thus creating a C-N bond.
An non-proteinogenic L-alpha-amino acid in which the amino group bears one or more methyl groups.
An amino acid derivative in which at least one of the hydrogens of the amino group has been replaced by a methyl group.
The six-membered ring form of D-fucose.
The pyranose form of L-fucose.
A N(6)-acyl-L-lysine having (2R,3R)-3-methyl-3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrol-2-ylcarbonyl as the N(6)-acyl group.
An N-acyl-D-glucosamine 1-phosphate in which the phosphate group of 2-(acetylamino)-2-deoxyglucose 1-phosphate is esterified by the alcoholic hydroxy group of L-serine.
An L-cysteine thioether that is S-(2E,6E)-farnesyl-L-cysteine bearing a hydroxy substituent on the pro-Z-methyl group at the 12-position.
An S-polyprenyl-L-cysteine where the polyprenyl moiety is specified as farnesyl.
An S-polyprenyl-L-cysteine where the polyprenyl moiety is specified as geranylgeranyl.
An organosulfur compound having the structure R2S=O or R2C=S=O (R =/= H).
A phosphoamino acid consisting of L-cysteine carrying an S-phospho substituent.
Compounds with the general formula RNHC(=O)CH3.
A tricarboxylic acid trianion that is the conjugate base of aconitic acid.
A tricarboxylic acid that is prop-1-ene substituted by carboxy groups at positions 1, 2 and 3.

An amino acid derivative resulting from reaction of alanine at the amino group or the carboxy group, or from the replacement of any hydrogen of alanine by a heteroatom. The definition normally excludes peptides containing alanine residues.
A hexaric acid resulting from formal oxidative ring cleavage of allose.
